The  alumni association of Adeniran Ogunsanya College of Education, Oto/Ijanikin, has said the upgrade of the school to a university will help create more graduate teachers for Lagos State primary and post-primary schools. The PUNCH reported that the Lagos State House of Assembly had approved the upgrade of Adeniran Ogunsanya College of Education and Michael Otedola College of Education to Lagos State University of Education. The National President of the association, Dr Shina Akintolure, in a statement signed by National Public Relations Officer, Mr Opeyemi Eniola, said there were structures and infrastructure that could accommodate the university. It said, “With the take-off of the University of Education it will help in the adequate supply of graduate teachers to Lagos State primary and post-primary schools. “The College is blessed with adequate manpower landmass and the closeness to Ogun State on the west and will attract students from neighbouring Ogun State and foreign countries of Benin, Togo, Ghana, and Côte d’Ivoire.” It also commended the Speaker of the Lagos State House of Assembly, Mr Mudashiru Obasa, for passing the bill. “We appreciate the alumni of the Adeniran Ogunsanya College of Education in the assembly; Mr Ibraheem Layode and Mr Sanai Agunbiade,” the statement added.” Copyright PUNCH. All rights reserved. This material, and other digital content on this website, may not be reproduced, published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed in whole or in part without prior express written permission from PUNCH. Contact: theeditor@punchng.com